Upon cleaning out the dusty old attic in my great grandmother’s home I discovered this illustration dated 1645 and titled “Die Dünder Füny”. There was an inscription in German on the back. See, half of my lineage on my mother’s side dates back to the Germanic tribes who once inhabited all of Bavaria. And my Great, Great, Grandmother was a Teutonic witch who was known for scolding spells to help out with unscrupulous children. Anyway, we had the writings on the back translated and this is what I found. The “Dünder Füny” pronounced (doon-der foon-ē) is a demon rabbit clothed in a dead puritan’s rags who punishes scurrilous children by stealing their Easter eggs and replacing them with rotten, black, festering eggs filled with chickadee corpses and maggots. Oh, but that’s not the end…this dark hare from the underworld has seven foot long ears that drag through manure fields, they reek and leave a trail of disease and germs. It also carries a large cast iron skillet that it uses to fry the children’s easter eggs into charred ovum of indifference. To top off the horror, The Dünder Füny also has a penchant for sneaking into homes and ripping off the heads of baby dolls which he likes to wear as a belt. 
Happiest Easter!
#myth #legend #folklore #drawing #ink #easter #easterbunny

“The Kingdom” is a watercolor on paper  painting standing at 35 x 52 inches. Depicting a woman standing like an obelisk in a dying field. She is structure and strength, a monolith grounded to the earth, and a conduit of power. She is surrounded by the brutality of life, the cold and harsh mountains, the wick tree attempting a death grip as it struggles for life. A wild hunt is ferociously happening around her as the bobcat readies to dispatch a panicked pheasant. All this chaos swirls around her yet she still stands steadfast and stoic, a beacon, a modern mother who is able to navigate and nurture “The Kingdom”. See it in my new exhibition “Paracosm” @stonesparrownyc

“Nimrod Ascending” - oil on linen - A representation of the biblical hunter and king of Mesopotamia who was responsible for The Tower Of Babel. This led to a reputation of rebellion against God. My Nimrod stands in defiance of all who challenge, ancient through modern, ushering in a rebellion against all who doubt. This is the stuff that comes from people telling you that you can’t be an artist when you grow up…something that I heard a lot in the 80’s. If you’re in NYC you can check it out right now through May 27 @stonesparrownyc in the Village.

“H. americanus” - oil painting on board. Titled for the species name of the American lobster, who’s giant crusher claw is featured dominantly in cadmium red, cad yellow, alizarin crimson, and raw umber. The figure stands cradling the claw, gently, as to take care of the specimen while the naturalist gazes upon, studying, logging, memorizing what stands before. Or perhaps a portrait of great importance that would hang in a grand library at the most enlightened institute of academia. A heroine of oceanography and naturalism, the great Maria Mitchell maybe? I do believe the continued exploration of the relationship between animals and humans is a key point to my education, evolution, and inspiration as an artist. Swipe through to see this paintings progression. The painting is now on view @stonesparrownyc in my exhibition “Paracosm” which runs through May 27. Contact the gallery for availability.

“Girl with Dumbo Octopus“ - oil painting on board. Throughout history we have seen portraits with women and animals. From Davinci’s “Lady With An Ermine”, to Holbein the Younger’s “Portrait of a Lady With A Squirrel and a Starling”, to Bouguereau’s “L'oiseau” or “The Bird” and on and on…the inspiration is endless. In my world, a fascinating deep sea exploration discovering a Dumbo Octopus would be as good as gold. But, in Spielberg fashion, a la E.T., once an alien is discovered, science is on the move to study, vivisect, and weaponize it. Not always, but it makes for a good story. And here, in my painting, is that moment when the story’s hero, who has established an unbreakable bond with our alien creature holds on with everything she can to save it. You can visit this inseparable duo @stonesparrownyc in my current exhibition “Paracosm” until May 27.

“Last Tango In Xochimilco” - watercolor on paper.

Once upon a time, by Lake Xochimilco,
A lonely Axolotl sat, feeling oh-so-low,
With a bandoneon on his knee, and a broken heart,
He played a tango, hoping for a new start.

The water hoppers came and went, as did the spring,
But the Axolotl kept playing, with a sorrowful ring,
He longed for his lost love, who once danced with glee,
But now she was gone, leaving him in misery.

The box would squeeze, and the air would sing,
But without his love, it meant nothing, no zing,
The smell of flowers would come and go,
But his heartache remained, a constant flow.

Oh, how the Axolotl wished for his love to return,
To dance a furious romance, and forget the burn,
Alas, she was gone, and he was left alone,
To play a tango to no one, with a mournful tone.

And so, the curious creature serenaded on,
A bittersweet melody, of love lost and gone,
But in his heart, he knew, someday, she might hear,
And they'd dance once again, without a single tear.

See it @stonesparrownyc until May 27

“Louisiana” - oil painting on linen- With this painting, I wanted to conjure up a unique visual representation of Louisiana. The muse could be seen as the goddess of music, inspiring the local musicians and infusing the air with the sounds of the fiddle. However, her position atop the alligator also suggests a more dangerous side, perhaps that of a siren who lures unsuspecting travelers into the murky waters of the bayous. The alligator could be a symbol of power and strength which represents the untamed wildness of the area. Overall, I wanted to blend the beauty of music with the primal, untamed nature of the bayous, creating a potent and intriguing symbol of the region. 
On view @stonesparrownyc through May 27

"C. carcharias, Death From Above." -oil painting on linen- The title refers to the Great White Shark, whose bleached jaws encircle the figure's face in the painting. The figure is holding up the jaws with a surprised expression, seemingly questioning why this creature is demonized, glorified, protected, and has this fish really been around for over 400 million years? The desaturated palette of the painting, painted in shades of white, creates a chilly atmosphere that is emphasized by the muse's woollen sweater, suggesting a stark, cold, and lonely environment where an apex predator might roam. However, the real question posed by the painting is who the true apex predator is.
On view now @stonesparrownyc until May 27

“Sphyrnidae” - oil on linen -

Transport yourself to a captivating tableau where a woman sits, her face etched with melancholy, beckoning the viewer to engage in a poignant duel of sensitivity. In this extraordinary scene, set within the confines of a long-abandoned factory, an inconceivable sight awaits. A massive 245-pound hammerhead shark has inexplicably found its way into the defunct bathroom. This arresting image has resided within the recesses of my mind for countless years, its origin and purpose a mystery even to myself. Initially, the woman in my original sketch for this painting exuded an air of triumph, but as the final piece took form, an overwhelming sense of empathy permeated the canvas. Now, the completed painting reverberates with a resounding cry for understanding. Does the passage of time possess the ability to soften harsh realities and bestow smoothness upon our experiences? I, too, find solace in the notion of being akin to a fine whiskey, maturing gracefully with age. Let us embark on a journey together, embracing the profound and the whimsical, as we contemplate the enigmatic nature of existence with a touch of joy and wonder in my exhibition “Paracosm” @stonesparrownyc until next weekend

“The Magpie And The Mushroom”
-watercolor on paper-

On a gloomy dawn
Magpie found a shiny stone
She landed on a mushroom cap
Who was often found alone

To the mushroom’s surprise
She perched upon his bow
The mushroom asked politely, 
“Could you get down now?”

Ever gregarious magpie said,
“Come with me. Let’s go and play!”
“No, thank you”, mushroom softly said,
“I’m fine right here. I think I’ll stay.”

This is a portrait of my children. My daughter has always been our magpie, collecting shiny things and getting into mischief. Our son, we’ll he would much prefer to sit on the couch and grow. 

This is the last week to see it @stonesparrownyc in my exhibition “Paracosm”

“Rey Del Mar”
- watercolor on paper-

The King of the sea. In a serene solitude, an ancient voyager king sits atop a throne crafted from coral, his presence commanding over the vast expanse of the seven seas. His wisdom is as ancient as time itself. Instead of portraying Triton as a merman exuding strength and power, I envisioned him as a symbol of knowledge, wisdom, and age. Resting in one flipper, he holds an organic rust trident, a testament to the might and historical significance of oceanic rulers.
To capture this essence, I chose a sea turtle as the embodiment of the character. With their long lifespan and innate wanderlust, I imagine sea turtles must accumulate a wealth of knowledge during their extensive travels. The painting, rendered in watercolor, embraces hues of greens and pinks, expanding my usual palette and artistic style. I feel that the image captures the enchanting essence of a child's vivid imagination, resonating with my deep aesthetic and emotional connection to folklore, mythology, and fables.

It is the last few days to see him @stonesparrownyc in my “Paracosm” exhibition, closes May 27.

“The Forest” - oil on linen - a portrait of my son - collection of the artist 

In a mystical blend of reality and wonder, a solitary boy sits amid the shadows of a hauntingly dark forest. His face, filled with curiosity, is illuminated by the soft glow emanating from an ethereal giant jellyfish, its radiant presence suspended before him. As if drawn together by cosmic fate, the boy extends his hand, fingertip outstretched, reaching out to make contact with the alien creature, bridging the gap between the ordinary and the extraordinary. This enchanted scene pays homage to the chance encounters of E.T. and Close Encounters of the Third Kind, where the boundaries of possibility blur, unveiling a world where the extraordinary is but a touch away.

In my painting titled "Mumbo Jumbo," we find ourselves in a mysterious and undisclosed location, where a captivating scene unfolds. Nestled in a dimly lit corner, an uakari, a mischievous monkey, holds a cauldron filled with a bubbling and ominous concoction, contained within the hollowed-out skull of a human. This simian figure may serve as a loyal companion to an evil wizard, aiding in the creation of a potion with sinister intent. Surrounding the monkey's perch are scattered bits and bobs, lending an air of disarray to the scene. A stack of ancient grimoires serves as the monkey's perch, hinting at the knowledge of dark arts it possesses. As the chilly winter air seeps in through an old window, it casts a cold backlight that heightens the atmospheric tension. In the realm of villainy, it is customary for such malevolent characters to have a wicked pet, and this uakari, with its cunning and devious expression, is certainly no exception. “Mumbo Jumbo”, oil on board. Private Collection. 2019

“H.mamillatus” -oil on board- available @stanekgallery 

The pencil urchin, an intriguing and beautiful sea creature, gracefully sways its spines underwater. These thick, rounded spines serve multiple purposes, enabling it to bore into surfaces and protect itself from predators, wave drag, and pressure. The layered structure of H. mammillatus' spines also allows them to deflect cracks, maintaining their hardened elegance like a starburst brooch when collected. Inspired by its allure, I depict it as the centerpiece of my painting—a 1940s hair accessory symbolizing feminine style, elegance, and power, like Billie Holiday’s iconic gardenia. 

#sea #portrait #oceanlife #painting #oilpainting

Another painting from long ago, "The Mouth of God," captures a captivating dichotomy that embodies the eternal struggle of opposites. The primordial, ancient spirit of the great white shark surrounds a serene and modern symbol of holiness, the white dove with outstretched wings. Against the backdrop of a black abyss, symbolizing the vast unknown, this dichotomy exemplifies the constant push and pull between conflicting elements, mirroring the dualities inherent in life - war and peace, light and darkness, internal and external. It prompts contemplation on the very essence of divinity and the enigmatic nature of existence. -Happy Shark Week!

The siren theme has been a haunting presence in my artwork, as I have always been fascinated by mythology and the concept that beauty, whether it comes through sight, song, or sweetness, can be dangerously alluring. It embodies the ultimate temptation, the pinnacle of sin, and the ultimate undoing.

In my painting titled "Siren," I capture the essence of this concept. The muse, donned in the traditional purity of a wedding gown, assumes a classical pose. At first glance, she appears enticing, beckoning with a seductive gaze over her shoulder. However, upon closer examination, a chilling revelation unfolds. The veil that shrouds her face is not merely a delicate fabric; instead, it is upheld by a set of menacing shark jaws, tightly embracing her countenance. This juxtaposition between ethereal beauty and the predatory nature of the shark symbolizes the fatal aspect of allure.

I take great pleasure in expressing the notion that within the epitome of beauty lies certain demise. It is a reminder that fascination and desire, when not approached with caution, can lead to dangerous consequences. Through this artwork, I seek to delve into the complexities of human nature, the duality of attraction, and the timeless allure of the siren myth. 

-Let’s go Shark Week!-

“Until Sabbath” - watercolor on paper - Private Collection -

In this watercolor painting, I portray the timeless theme of the shepherdess. The central figure tenderly carries a stray goat back to the herd, shrouded by the mist-filled day. Yet, within this tranquil setting, the question arises: will the goat be reunited with its kind on the farm, or does a darker fate await, possibly involving a witches' sabbath and sacrificial rituals? This subtle interplay of light and shadow stirs a sense of intrigue and mystery, evoking emotions that lie beneath the surface of this otherwise serene image. Cheeky titles and classic images always light my 🔥.
#art #watercolor #watercolorpainting #sabbath #goat #witch

“Breathing The Breath Of The Bold” 
- watercolor on paper - 
Private Collection-

In my expansive triptych watercolor, I aimed to encapsulate three facets of youth. The jester, the solitary innocent, and the tumultuously destructive. Whether fostering camaraderie through playful antics, embarking on a journey of self-discovery through introspection, or embracing chaos by engaging in reckless behaviors resulting in a car burning. This composition also symbolizes the cycle of life, from birth to demise. The artwork employs the symbolism of threes, adhering to the rule of thirds and the universal triadic ratio. Each segment represents one facet, with opposing sides and an underlying truth. This omnipresent theme intertwines with a collage of delightful elements, resulting in a harmonious amalgamation.

“She Crab” 
In my original oil painting, I portray a sea maiden exquisitely adorned with pearls woven into her hair. Yet, it's the commanding presence of a massive Dungeness crab choker that truly captures the eye, encircling her neck like a regal emblem. This artwork weaves together contrasting elements—a regal mermaid with an unyielding exterior, poised to conquer the challenges of the terrestrial realm. Perhaps a playful pun or a fantastical concept, it could even serve as inspiration for the cherished tradition of she crab soup. 😀🦀
The original painting is long gone into a private collection but you can have an archival ink on watercolor version.
